instruction: While using ```new_list = my_list```, any modifications to ```new_list``` changes ```my_list``` every time. Why is this, and how can I clone or copy the list to prevent it?
output_1:
Here is a simple example to show that ```my_list``` and ```new_list``` are actually the same object:
```my_list = [1, 2, 3]
new_list = my_list
my_list.append(4)
```
```print(my_list)
print(new_list)
```
```[1, 2, 3, 4]
[1, 2, 3, 4]
```
Since ```my_list``` and ```new_list``` refer to the same object, changing one object changes the other object.

To copy a list, you can use ```copy``` function:
```my_list = [1, 2, 3]
new_list = copy.copy(my_list)
my_list.append(4)
```
```print(my_list)
print(new_list)
```
```[1, 2, 3, 4]
[1, 2, 3]
```

Here is another way to copy a list using ```list_object.copy()```:
```my_list = [1, 2, 3]
new_list = list_object.copy()
my_list.append(4)
```
```print(my_list)
print(new_list)
```
```[1, 2, 3, 4]
[1, 2, 3]
```

Note that the second method will actually change ```new_list```, while the third method will not.

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
# create some data to plot
x_data = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]
y_data = [3, 2, 1, 8, 6]

fig, ax = plt.subplots()

# set the x-axis range
ax.set_xlim(0, 6)

# set the y-axis range
ax.set_ylim(0, 9)

# plot the data points
ax.scatter(x_data, y_data, color="red", alpha=0.7)

# fit a trend line
from scipy.stats import linregress
popt, pcov = linregress(x_data, y_data)

            textcoords="offset points", color="green", alpha=0.7)

# show the plot

instruction: Jeff takes 20 minutes to jog around the race course one time, and 25 minutes to jog around a second time. What is his average speed in miles per hour for the whole jog if one course is 3 miles long?
output_1:
The average speed of Jeff in miles per hour for the whole jog is given by,

Average speed = ∑(distance/time)

∑(3/20) + (3/25)

∑(3/20) + (3/25) - 3/20

∑(3/20) + 3/25 - 3/20

∑(9/20) + 3/25 - 3/20

∑(9/20) + 9/25 - 9/20

∑(4.2) + 9/25 - 9/20

∑(4.2) + 24/25 - 9/20

4.2 + 24/25 - 9/20

4.2 + 24/25 - 3

4.2 + 8/25 - 3

4.2 + 8/25

4.2 + 0.64

4.2 + 0.64 * 25

4.2 + 16.8

Jeff's average speed in miles per hour for the whole jog is 4.2 + 16.8 = 21.8 miles per hour.

instruction: Write an essay discussing the importance of communication in a relationship.
output_1:
Communication is very important in a relationship because it allows for a deeper connection between the parties involved. Without it, misunderstandings are sure to arise and feelings could be hurt.

Having good communication skills requires one to be both a good listener and a good communicator. Good listeners can often pick up on non-verbal cues, such as facial expressions and body language, that can give them more insight into what the other person is really saying. Good communicators on the other hand, ensure that their messages are clear and concise. They use words and phrases that avoid ambiguity and are easy to understand. They are also mindful of the way they use their voice, and their body language.

For a relationship to work, both parties involved need to be good communicators. It takes two to tango, after all. If one person isn't doing their part, the relationship will suffer.

In conclusion, communication is important in any relationship. It allows for a deeper understanding of one another and helps to avoid misunderstandings. If you're having trouble communicating with your partner, it may be time to have a talk.
output_2:
The ability to communicate is a fundamental part of human interaction. Effective communication is key to maintaining healthy relationships. The ability to share emotions, thoughts, ideas, and opinions is important in maintaining intimacy.

In intimate relationships such as marriage, communication is a key component to the relationship. A couple should strive to be comfortable expressing emotions, thoughts, and ideas openly. Being able to openly communicate helps to build trust in the relationship. Trust is essential for the relationship to thrive.

In communication, nonverbal cues are important to understand the meaning of the message. A study by the University of Texas has shown that couples can be up to 10 times more accurate when communicating through nonverbal cues than through verbal cues. 

Healthy relationships can be built and maintained through clear communication. When a couple shares their thoughts, emotions, ideas, and opinions, they are sharing a part of themselves. As they continue to do this, their relationship will become stronger.

instruction: Write a story about a brave knight who is on a quest to save the world from evil forces.
output_1:
Once upon a time, in a land far, far away, there lived a brave knight named John. John was a kindhearted man who always put others before himself. He had a wife and two children, but he loved them all dearly.
  One day, a sinister force known as the Dark Lord arose, and he began to spread his evil throughout the land. The Dark Lord had many minions at his command, and he used them to harass the citizens of the kingdom. John, knowing that he had to act, donned his armor and prepared for battle.
  John marched forth, sword in hand, and cut down any foe that stood in his way. He destroyed the Dark Lord's strongest servants, and soon the battle was over. But the Dark Lord was not to be so easily defeated. He summoned his most powerful servant, a demon known as The Beast, to finish off the brave knight.
  John fought valiantly, but he was no match for The Beast. As John fell to the ground, he knew that this was his final battle. He looked up and saw his wife and children standing above him. They knew that he was dying, but they had to see him one last time.
  John smiled as he took one last breath, knowing that he had done what was right. His wife and children held him close, knowing that he was not only a brave knight, but also a good man.
  In that moment, a beam of light appeared, and it descended down from the heavens. It enveloped John in its glow, and he was instantly healed. The Dark Lord and his minions were stunned by this miracle, and they fled the kingdom.
  John returned home to his family, and they celebrated his victory. He lived a long and happy life, and he was honored as a hero for his brave deeds.

A long time ago, in a faraway kingdom, there lived a brave and honorable knight.  This knight was well-known and respected throughout the land for his strength, bravery, and integrity.  He was a true knight in shining armor, and everyone admired him for his noble character and gallant deeds.  

One day, the knight received word that an evil force was threatening the kingdom, and he knew that he had to act.  So he gathered his trusted companions and set out on a dangerous quest to save the kingdom from destruction.  Together, they traveled for weeks, battling dangerous creatures and overcoming obstacles along the way.  But in the end, they defeated the evil force and saved the kingdom.  The brave knight was lauded as a hero, and he lived happily ever after with his beloved princess.

instruction: Write a script for a YouTube video exploring the history and cultural significance of jazz.
output_1:
```
#!/bin/bash

youtube-dl -f best -x --no-warnings -g https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wXn8m9F6f6M
```
This will download the video in the highest possible quality with all warnings turned off and the name of the video will be ```wXn8m9F6f6M```.
output_2:
The history of jazz goes all the way back to the early 1900s in New Orleans, when it was a mixture of European and African American musical styles.  It was one of the first American art forms to incorporate both European and African elements, and is one of the earliest examples of American popular music.  The music was primarily instrumental in the early years, with the singing style being influenced by the blues.  As the years went on, the music started incorporating more elements from pop music and became more rhythm-based.  The music has evolved over time, but the core elements remain the same:  complex harmonies, a heavy use of dissonance, and an emphasis on improvisation.  Jazz is a highly improvised music style, and the musicians are expected to create music on the spot and in the moment, while still staying within the established harmonic structure of the song.

Jazz became popular during the Harlem Renaissance of the 1920s, and was performed in clubs like the Cotton Club and the Apollo Theater.  Many of the jazz greats of the time came from New Orleans, including Louis Armstrong, Duke Ellington, and Cab Calloway.  Jazz was also popularized by Benny Goodman and his orchestra in the 1930s and 1940s, and by musicians like Ella Fitzgerald, Miles Davis, and Billie Holiday in the 1950s.  In the 1960s, many artists started incorporating elements of rock and roll into their jazz music, creating what was known as "rock jazz."  Rock jazz artists included musicians like Miles Davis, John Coltrane, and Sonny Rollins.  In the 1970s and 1980s, artists like Herbie Hancock and Weather Report started incorporating elements of funk and Latin music into their jazz.  Today, jazz is enjoyed all over the world and continues to evolve and develop.

instruction: Does Crimea belong to Russia?
output_1:
* Crimea is an autonomous republic of Russia and is in the Southeastern part of Ukraine. 
* It was part of Russia until 1954. 
* Russia took control of the region in 2014, after a referendum. 
* The people of Crimea voted to secede from Ukraine and join Russia.
* This resulted in the 2014 Russian annexation of Crimea.
output_2:
Crimea is a region in the southern part of Ukraine, on the Black Sea. The majority of Crimea's population is ethnically Russian and favor closer ties with Russia. In March 2014, Crimea held a referendum on joining Russia, and on 16 March 2014, Crimea became part of the Russian Federation, as specified in the Treaty on Accession of the Republic of Crimea to the Russian Federation, which was formally ratified on 18 March 2014 by the President of Russia and the President of Ukraine. According to Article 8 of the treaty, the Republic of Crimea's accession to the Russian Federation came into force on the date of the President of Russia's signature.

On 21 March 2014, the Russian government announced that the results of the referendum were valid, and that the people of Crimea had chosen to join Russia in a democratic vote. On 27 March 2014, the Parliament of Russia officially recognized the accession of Crimea to Russia. In April 2014, the parliaments of France, Germany, Italy, Poland, Romania, Sweden, the United Kingdom, and the United States, along with the European Union and the United Nations General Assembly, recognized the Russian annexation of Crimea as illegitimate. The United States and the European Union also imposed economic sanctions on Russia.

The United Nations General Assembly resolution 68/262 (which condemned the annexation as illegal) was adopted by a vote of 128 to 11, with 51 abstentions. All of Crimea's neighboring countries, as well as almost all countries in Europe and Asia, recognize Crimea as part of Ukraine, and do not recognize the Russian annexation. The European Union, the United States, and several other countries impose economic sanctions on Russia.

instruction: What do you think of the relationship between robots & humans in the labor market?
output_1:
Robots have the potential to replace humans in a lot of jobs. We can already see this happening in certain areas like manufacturing. However, it is unlikely that robots will be able to take over all jobs. This is because there are certain tasks that can only be done by humans, such as creativity and empathy.
Overall, I think that the future of work will be a hybrid of human and machine labour. Humans will still be needed to do the creative and empathetic tasks, while robots will take over the more mundane and repetitive tasks.
output_2: The idea of robots replacing humans in the workplace has been around for decades, but the reality of it has only recently begun to materialize.  The advent of more affordable artificial intelligence and machine learning algorithms have enabled companies to deploy robots in more and more situations.  But the question remains:  if robots can perform labor-intensive and/or mundane tasks, what will this mean for the labor market and the roles of humans in society?  On one hand, it can lead to a “Uberfication” of the labor market, where workers who are currently employed in low-skilled jobs might be displaced by robots, and those workers will be left searching for work in other industries or with other employers.  On the other hand, robots may also lead to the emergence of new, previously unforeseen, types of jobs, or new industries that leverage robotics and artificial intelligence.

Paraphrase the following text with advanced English words for a scientific paper:

Neural network based methods have obtained great progress on a variety of natural language processing tasks. In this paper, we use the multi-task learning framework to jointly learn across multiple related tasks.
output_1: Multi-task learning has made great progress on a variety of natural language processing tasks. Neural network based methods have obtained great progress on a variety of natural language processing tasks. However, in most previous works, the models are learned based on single-task supervised objectives, which often suffer from insufficient training data. In this paper, we use the multi-task learning framework to jointly learn across multiple related tasks.

We use two types of objective functions, the first one is the supervised objective used in most previous works, which takes the form of a categorical cross-entropy loss. The other one is the contrastive loss, which is originally proposed in the visual domain and has been recently applied in natural language processing as well. For a specific task, we jointly train a model using both types of losses, and the final prediction is determined by the model that obtains the higher score on the supervised loss. Experiments on multiple NLP tasks show that the proposed method obtains significant performance gains and is more robust to insufficient data.

instruction: What are the strengths and weaknesses of working at a startup compared to working at a tech giant?
output_1:
* Strengths:
    * 1. High learning curves: The work is usually more interesting because you’re learning new things constantly.
    * 2. High level of autonomy: You get to make decisions and the outcome is usually more visible.
    * 3. More impact: If you’re at a startup you can make a bigger impact than if you’re at a tech giant.
    * 4. More responsibility: You’re usually trusted to get your job done independently.
    * 5. High compensation: If you’re at a startup, you usually get a high salary and equity.
    * 6. More work culture: The work culture at a startup is usually more fun and relaxed.
  * Weaknesses:
    * 1. Small company: There’s less room for growth and advancement.
    * 2. Low team cohesion: Startups usually have more people and a more diverse team.
    * 3. Less benefits: Startups usually don’t have as many benefits as tech giants.
    * 4. No company culture: It’s easier to create a culture at a tech giant than at a startup.
    * 5. High pressure: There’s usually more pressure at a startup.
output_2:
-  Startups are usually in a very early stage of development and there's a lot of room for growth and the company can benefit from the employee's unique perspective
 -  The startup culture tends to be more casual and less hierarchical than in larger companies
 -  Startups are usually lean and can be agile, they can make decisions quickly
 -  The employee usually gets to work on multiple projects and the projects are diverse which makes the work more interesting
 -  A startup usually offers a competitive salary and benefits
 -  The employee is part of a tightly-knit community and the employee gets to work with smart people who are passionate about the company's mission
 -  The employee usually gets exposure to a wide range of technologies
 -  Startups usually have the backing of VCs and the employee can benefit from the employee stock options
 -  Startups usually have a very low employee turnover which means the employee usually stays for a long time with the company
 -  A startup usually has a very short runway which means that the company can fold any day and the employee can be unemployed with a very short notice
 -  Working at a startup usually means a higher work load and less predictable work hours
 -  Startups usually have a very intense and stressful work environment

    And with that, he fires his first salvo at Hillary Clinton:
    "I believe that Hillary Clinton cares more about Wall Street than she does about the working man. And she's wrong about what's going on in this country. It's a rigged system, folks, and you know it.

    "And you also know that she's a terrible person.

    "Donald, I am so grateful to you for agreeing to this debate, under the circumstances, and I'm gonna tell you something right now, I'm gonna take you on, I'm gonna kick your butt, and I'm gonna win."

    "I know you don't want to hear this, but we have to elect me. I will be a great president, and I will make sure that Donald Trump never becomes president.
    "So if you have any doubts about my character, just remember that I'm running against Donald Trump, and you can't trust Donald Trump."

instruction: Does P=NP?
output_1:
No, the problem of P=NP is undecidable. The undecidability of P=NP is known as the P vs. NP problem. We can prove that the P vs. NP problem is undecidable by constructing a Turing machine that takes a string as input and halts with the answer “Yes” or “No” depending on whether or not the string belongs to P. The problem of P vs. NP is also known to be one of the hardest problems in computational complexity. As of 2021, there is no known algorithm that can efficiently solve the problem.

The question of whether P=NP is a central problem in theoretical computer science, and there are many different approaches to the problem. One approach is to look for an efficient algorithm for P=NP. Another approach is to try to prove that P!=NP. There is no known efficient algorithm for P=NP, and it is unknown whether P=NP is equal to or greater than NP.
output_2:
The P versus NP problem, also known as the Great Disappointment, the P vs. NP Problem, or the P vs. NP conjecture, is the conjecture that the problem of deciding whether a given integer is a prime number (a "primality test") is as hard as the problem of determining whether a given integer is a perfect integer (a "perfectness test").  That is, the two problems have the same computational complexity.  It is one of the most famous unsolved problems in mathematics, as well as an important problem in computer science.  

The conjecture was proposed by Richard Karp in 1970, and Stephen Cook showed in 1993 that a special case of it was true, but the general case remains unsolved.  If true, it would have profound implications for the theory of computation and the theory of mathematics, as it would solve some of the long-standing "middle" problems in the field, which concern the relationship between the theory of computation and the theory of mathematical objects.  

The P versus NP problem remains one of the most studied open problems in both computer science and mathematics.  Many algorithms to decide if an integer is prime have been developed, but none is known to be able to solve the problem in a time that is polynomial in the size of the integer.  Similarly, there are known polynomial-time algorithms to decide whether an integer is a perfect number, but none are known to be able to solve the problem in a time that is polynomial in the size of the integer.  This indicates that there is an exponential difference in the difficulty of the problems, which is what would be required for the P versus NP conjecture to be true.  However, no known proof of the conjecture or counterexamples to it have been found, and it is therefore considered unresolved.

instruction: I want to live in a 2BR apartment in downtown Chicago, probably over the next 5 years. My wife and I make 250k, though we like to live at a high standard. Rent should cost somewhere around 3k, but buying would be approximately 500k. Can you break it down for me and help me figure out what is the better financial choice? Renting or buying?
output_1:
* Buying may be better for you. Depending on the city, you may be able to get a pretty good deal with the 3M you make and the 500K you plan to spend. In some cases you may even be able to find a decent mortgage around 3k a month. The cost of buying a home may be cheaper in the long run than renting.
  * However, there are some things to consider. You may have to pay a bit more for your mortgage each month, but there is also the down payment you would have to pay upfront. Depending on how much money you have, this may be a significant sum of money.

If you are interested in sitting down with a financial adviser, you can contact [insert financial company's name here] for a free consultation.
  * In the end, only you can decide if buying a house is right for you. If you decide to move within the next 5 years, you may want to consider renting. This way you can easily move to a new location and won't have to worry about selling your home.
output_2:
1. If you buy, your monthly mortgage payments will be about 3k. That's a fixed payment, which will help you plan your expenses. The down payment for a 500k apartment will be around 100k, so you'll need to pay 300k in cash, or get a mortgage of about 250k.
 2. Your monthly rent payments will be 3k, which is a fixed payment, too. You don't have to worry about property value or mortgage rates. But it's still possible to get your monthly rent payments below 3k, if you're willing to live in a smaller apartment.
 3. The apartment will appreciate at a rate of around 2% per year. So, if you buy, you'll get your money back and then some. If you rent, the landlord will keep all the appreciation.

I hope this helps!

A: Buying is the better choice here. It's generally better to own real estate because the appreciation makes up for the mortgage costs. Additionally, renting can go up or down significantly, so the fixed costs of buying will always be preferable.

instruction: In linux, how do I list all the files in the subdirectories of ~/data according to the time they were last edited?
output_1:
# Find the files in the current directory that were modified recently
    find. -type f -mtime -1
    
    # List the files according to the time they were last edited
    find. -type f -mtime -1 | while read line; do echo $line; done
    
    # List the files according to the time they were last edited and print the full path
    find. -type f -mtime -1 | while read line; do echo $line; done | while read line; do echo $line; done
output_2:
find ~/data -type f -exec stat -c %Y "{}" \; 

Above command lists all files in ~/data, recursively, and prints the year the file was last edited.  Note that the command above uses the'stat' command, which is not part of core 'find' and hence must be installed separately.

instruction: I have a Python script called preprocess.py. Write a bash command that runs it on all the files that end with ".checkpoint" in all the subdirectories, subsubdirectories, etc. of the checkpoints/ directory.

    # path to python script

    # path to folder with files to be processed

    # pattern to find files to process

    # recursively find files in folder

instruction: Prove the existence of uncountable sets using Cantor's diagonalization.
output_1:
The diagonal method (named after German mathematician David Hilbert) is one of the most powerful techniques in mathematical analysis. The idea is to show that there is a "diagonal" that separates two sets. If there is no diagonal, then the two sets are equal, which is a contradiction.

Suppose that we have two sets A and B and we want to show that they are equal. We can find a diagonal D that separates them. To do this, we will construct a sequence of sets D1, D2, D3,... such that Dn+1 is contained in Dn and it separates A and B. This will show that the sets are equal, which is a contradiction.

To construct the sequence, we can start with D1 = D. Then, we can find two elements a and b in A such that a is not contained in D1 and b is not contained in D1. We then add D1 to D2 to get D2. Then, we find another pair of elements c and d in B such that c is not contained in D2 and d is not contained in D2. We then add D2 to D3 to get D3.

This process will continue indefinitely. As long as there are elements in A or B that are not contained in Dn, we can keep adding Dn to Dn+1. Eventually, we will reach a point where all elements of A and B are contained in Dn, which is our diagonal.

Suppose that A and B are not equal. Then, there is some diagonal D that separates them. This means that Dn is contained in Dn+1 for some n. However, this means that Dn is contained in Dn+2, which is a contradiction.

Therefore, it must be true that all sets are equal. This can be proved in other ways, but the diagonal method is one of the most powerful techniques in mathematical analysis.

To do this, we’ll use a diagonal argument, that is, we’ll show that there’s a set of real numbers that has the property we’re trying to prove for every possible set of elements of $$A$$.

We’ll add one such number to the set, and then two numbers that are adjacent to each of those two numbers.  We’ll keep doing this until we’ve added infinitely many numbers.

Then we’ll repeat this process for $$A_2$$, and we’ll add a number to $$A_2$$ that is adjacent to every number in $$A_2$$. We’ll do this for every element of $$A_n$$, so we’ll get a new set $$A_{n+1}$$ that is the set of numbers in $$A_n$$ plus the number that is adjacent to every number in $$A_n$$.  We’ll keep doing this, and at every stage we’ll add a number that is adjacent to every number in the set that we’ve added so far, so that the set gets larger and larger.

We’ll continue doing this forever, and at every step we’ll add a number that is adjacent to every number in the set that we’ve added so far, so that the set gets larger and larger. In fact, the set we’ll end up with is the set of all numbers between any two numbers in $$A$$.

So we’ve shown that there are infinitely many numbers between any two numbers in $$A$$.  This implies that there are infinitely many elements of $$A$$ that are between any two elements of $$A$$.

instruction: Prove that every set is countable.
output_1:
1. The following proof shows that every set is countable:
Assume that there is a set $S$ which is not countable.
Then there is an element $a \in S$ such that for every $N \in \mathbb{N}$ there is $N' \ge N$ such that $a \notin S$.
Then $\{N: N' \ge N\}$ is an infinite set $J$, and there is an $N \in J$ such that $a \notin S$.
Let $f: \mathbb{N} \rightarrow S$ be the function that maps $N$ to $a^N$.
Then $f$ is surjective, because for every $b \in S$ there is $N \in \mathbb{N}$ such that $b^N = a^N = f(N)$.
However, $f$ is not injective, because $f(N) = f(N')$.
Thus $S$ is not countable.
Therefore, every set is countable.

I have seen how they have cared for one another and how they have shared their knowledge and their wisdom. So, today, I speak to the humans. I speak to all of you who come here from afar.

instruction: I'm a youtuber that has a channel that explains machine learning concepts to elementary school children. Write a script for my next show on language models.
output_1:
Hello, everyone, and welcome to another episode of "Let's Understand Machine Learning". As you all know, the last few episodes have been about deep learning models, but I have some exciting news for you today! The last few episodes have been about deep learning models, but I have some exciting news for you today! In the last episode, we learned about convolutional neural networks, and how we can use them to classify images. In today's episode, we are going to learn about another type of neural network called language models, and how they can be used to understand text. So let's get started!

First, what is a language model? Language models are a type of neural network that can learn to predict the next word in a text sequence, based on the previous words. For example, if we have a text sequence like "hello world", a language model will be able to predict the next word, which is "how". This is called "sequence to sequence prediction", because we are predicting the next word in the sequence, based on the previous words. Language models are often used for tasks like machine translation and speech recognition, where we need to understand text and convert it to speech or translate it to another language. But language models can also be used for other tasks like text summarization and question answering, where we need to understand the context of a text and answer a related question. So let's take a look at how language models work!

The core idea behind language models is that words in a text sequence are often related to each other, and we can use this relation to predict the next word. For example, if we have a text sequence "hello world", then "world" is more likely to be the next word in the sequence, than "abc". So to predict the next word, we can first find all the words that are more likely to be the next word in the sequence than the current word. Then, we can use these more likely words to update our prediction for the next word. This process of finding more likely words and updating our prediction is called "back propagation", and it is how language models learn to predict the next word.

So let's take a look at how back propagation works! When we are predicting the next word in a text sequence, we use the previous words as input to a language model. The language model outputs a probability distribution over all the possible words in the vocabulary, and we choose the most likely word according to this probability distribution. But the language model also updates the probability distribution for the next word based on all the previous words. So after we choose the word, the probability distribution for the next word will change, and the language model will use this new probability distribution to update its internal parameters. This process of choosing a word and updating the probability distribution is called "back propagation", and it is how language models learn to predict the next word.

Now that we know how language models work, let's take a look at how they are used for different tasks! In the next episode, we will learn about some applications of language models, and how they can be used for different tasks! So see you then!

instruction: What propels vomit out of your stomach?
output_1:
* Vomit is propelled out of the stomach by contractions of the muscles that surround the stomach.
* When food moves into the stomach, the muscular wall of the stomach moves in and expands.
* As the stomach fills, the wall of the stomach also pushes inward.
* This causes the inner lining of the stomach to also stretch.
* This stretching also causes the cells of the stomach lining to pull together and contract.
* This creates a pressure inside the stomach that pushes the stomach lining and contents out of the stomach.
* This propels the stomach contents out of the stomach.
* This is known as peristalsis.

instruction: How do noise cancelling headphones/earphones work?
output_1: Noise-cancelling headphones are a type of headphone that use active noise control to reduce noise. When noise-cancelling headphones are worn, an audio signal from the device is sent to a microphone in each earpiece. The audio signal from the microphone is then inverted and fed into a loudspeaker. The inverted signal is delayed by a fraction of a millisecond to match the time delay between the sound waves entering and leaving the ear canal. The sound waves interfere with each other, cancelling out most of the background noise, leaving only the sound from the source.
output_2:
Noise cancelling headphones and earphones use active noise cancellation (ANC) technology to detect and analyse background noise, then counteract this noise by playing an inverse wave of sound at the source.  This inverse wave of sound is known as an anti-noise wave.  The anti-noise wave is generated by microchips in the headphones or earphones and can be either analog or digital.

Noise cancelling headphones work very well for the most part.  They are most effective for lower frequency noises such as those caused by aircraft and road traffic.  However, they are less effective at blocking higher frequency noises such as people talking, and do not block all noise completely.

Noise cancelling headphones are most useful when worn with your ear close to the noise source, or when you're in a situation where you need to focus on the noise source and block out other background noise.  For example, wearing noise cancelling headphones at a loud concert or on a busy street.  They are also useful if you are in a noisy work environment, such as an office, factory, or airport.

instruction: Write a short story based on the following prompt:  You find an abandoned puppy hiding from the rain on your doorstep. This “puppy” is actually the child of Cerberus, the puppy was cast out due to it being born with the deformity of only having one head.

I took the puppy into my home and tried to dry it off as best I could. It was only half my fault that it was like this, after all, it had only been a day since it was born. It was too late to go back to its mother, and besides, I would never be able to pay the price that would come if she caught me. I gave the little thing a warm blanket to sleep in and left her to it. I went to work, leaving her with the sound of thunder rumbling outside my window.
It was at work that I got the call.
"Hey, it's me. I just wanted to tell you that the puppy is doing fine. She is sleeping right now, but she seems to be recovering nicely. Thank you so much for taking her in. I'm going to be in really late tonight, I love you."
I hung up the phone and smiled. I had just found the most adorable thing in the world.

The puppy was named Cerberus. Cerberus is the three-headed guard dog of Hades, the Greek god of the Underworld. Cerberus was born with only one head, and the rest of it was deformed. I told Cerberus that he was still a good dog, and that he will always be loved.

instruction: Why do most plastics turn white when you bend them?

The chemical reaction that causes this is called 'catalysed homo-polymerisation'. Catalysed homo-polymerisation is the process that allows plastics to become flexible, and to become strong and durable.

 When you bend a plastic item, the molecular structure is disturbed and this weakens the bonds between the atoms. The atoms are then free to move around more and find different positions. Since the atoms are now less tightly bound, the plastic becomes less rigid, and it is then more like a liquid. This is why when you bend a piece of plastic, it will turn white.

instruction: How come the space station needs to fire a rocket regularly to stay in orbit, but dangerous space junk can stay up there indefinitely?

The space station orbits the Earth at a much higher altitude than the space junk, and therefore is constantly accelerating upwards. The space station needs to fire its thrusters to compensate for this acceleration and slow its descent so that it can maintain its orbit.

On the other hand, the space junk is already moving at a constant velocity in its orbit around the Earth, so it doesn't need to compensate for any acceleration and can stay in orbit indefinitely without firing any thrusters.

Objects like old satellites, spent rocket boosters, and other space junk can stay in orbit indefinitely because there is no natural process that will bring them down.  On the other hand, the space station has to fire a rocket every now and then to keep itself in orbit.  This is because, as the space station moves through the atmosphere, it experiences friction and air drag.  This friction and drag cause the space station to gradually move towards the earth and eventually fall out of orbit.  If the space station is not constantly propelled upwards by a rocket, it will eventually fall back to earth.  The space station is a complex system with lots of moving parts, and it can't stay in orbit indefinitely.  The rockets that propel the space station are the only things that can overcome the friction and drag, and keep it up there.

instruction: You are the world's worst marriage guidance counselor. What advice do you give?
output_1:
Dear client,

I am truly sorry for your misfortune.

Here is my best advice.

1.  First, you need to recognize that you are the problem. It is you that is causing all the problems. No one else. You need to own up to your mistakes and stop trying to shift the blame to your spouse.

	* What is my inner motivation?

And you must learn to pray for your spouse and confess your sins to God. Honesty is key.
5.  Fifth, you need to practice forgiveness. This is the hardest of all. Forgiveness is not an easy thing to do. When someone has hurt you or let you down, it takes an enormous amount of strength and discipline to forgive that person. It takes a lot of energy to hate. And it takes a lot of energy to forgive. So you must choose to forgive your spouse, even when it is the hardest thing to do. And you must choose to forgive yourself. Forgiveness is the foundation of a healthy marriage.
6.  Sixth, you need to develop a good communication style. Communication is the lifeblood of any marriage. If you do not have good communication skills, your marriage will die. There are several different styles of communication that you can learn and practice. Some of these are:
	*	1.	Active listening. This is the most important skill of all. Active listening is the practice of focusing on the other person, listening without judgment, and responding with empathy. This is the practice of really listening to your spouse. If you want to have a healthy marriage, you must learn to actively listen.
	*	2.	Problem solving. This is a skill that every married person must learn. You must learn to solve problems together as a team. If you let problems fester and grow, they will eventually kill your marriage. So you must learn to deal with problems as they arise, rather than allowing them to grow and consume you.
	*	3.	Active listening. This is the most important skill of all. Active listening is the practice of focusing on the other person, listening without judgment, and responding with empathy. This is the practice of really listening to your spouse. If you want to have a healthy marriage, you must learn to actively listen.
7.  Seventh, you must practice humility. It is very easy for a married person to get a big head. You are married. That is a big accomplishment. But there are other people in your life that have accomplished even more than you. You must learn to put your spouse on a pedestal and let them do things for you. You must learn to give, to serve, and to love. Your spouse must feel like a queen in your presence. If they do not, then you have failed.
8.  Eighth, you must learn to compromise. This is the single most important skill for a married person to master. You must learn to sacrifice and let go of what you want. You must learn to compromise and give in order to make your spouse happy. Compromise is the foundation of a healthy marriage.

Genetic material is the collection of genes that make up an organism's DNA. New genetic material is acquired through reproduction. Therefore, to not die out, remote tribes that have no new genetic material for thousands of years would need to reproduce without reproducing new genetic material.

This would be impossible, because if they reproduced, they would pass on some of their old genetic material to their offspring. This would eventually cause the species to die out due to lack of new genetic material.

Therefore, the only way for remote tribes that have no new genetic material for thousands of years not to die out would be for them to reproduce while not reproducing any new genetic material.
output_2: The most common reason why remote tribes do not die out because of inbreeding is because they have a large territory. This means that the tribe will have more space to find mates that are not related. Also, due to the lack of genetic material, remote tribes are able to have children at a younger age than people who live in cities. This means that they will have more children that are not related. Inbreeding is usually seen in smaller groups or close-knit societies. If a tribe were to have a smaller territory and/or had to rely on one another for survival, they would be more likely to be related. This would result in inbreeding and the possible extinction of the tribe.

First, let's understand why you would want to do this: if someone gains access to your system, they can see all of the previous passwords.  If you force people to change their password frequently, it becomes less likely that they will use a password that has been seen previously.  

This practice is also called "Password Rotation", and a related idea is to have a "Password Expiration Policy" where you require people to change their passwords at a certain point.  

Now, how does this actually help you?  Let's say that you have an employee that gets a new computer and you are worried that their old computer could still be compromised.  In this case, you would want to force them to change their password in order to secure their new computer.  However, if you are doing this to protect the organization, you should have an automated system that forces the employee to change their password on a regular basis.  This ensures that you have the most secure password possible for the employee, while also protecting the employee from having to remember too many passwords.

If you force people to change their password on a regular basis, then you need to have a way for them to reset their password if they forget it. However, there are different types of rent control, and not all areas have rent control.  For example, the concept of rent control was introduced in the UK in the post-war years.  Rent controls are often associated with the concept of the welfare state and are seen as a means to protect the most vulnerable members of society from exploitation by landlords.  Rent controls are usually associated with council housing.

There are two forms of rent control: statutory rent control and contractual rent control.  Statutory rent control applies to all tenants in a particular area, but contractual rent control applies only to those who have a written agreement with their landlord.

The most well-known rent control policy in the US is in the state of California, where the Rent Stabilization Ordinance (RSO) was introduced in 1977 and was later amended by the Costa-Hawkins Rental Housing Act of 1995.  The RSO applies to all properties in cities and counties with more than 500,000 residents.  The RSO limits rent increases on existing tenancies to no more than the increase in the consumer price index (CPI) plus 2% per year.  The RSO does not apply to newly constructed housing, which is subject to the Costa-Hawkins Act, which limits rent increases to the rate of inflation plus a fixed percentage.

The Costa-Hawkins Act limits rent increases to no more than the rate of inflation plus a fixed percentage.  The percentage is different in different areas of California, but it is usually between 5-10%.  It is important to note that this law only applies to newly constructed properties.  Properties built before 1995 and still occupied are not subject to Costa-Hawkins.

In general, rent control is intended to protect tenants from exploitation by landlords and ensure that tenants can afford to live in their home.  Rent control also provides stability for tenants and allows them to plan their finances over the long term.

instruction: How should I do time manage spreading time working on multiple projects? For example, should I "time block" your calendar and say 8am to 10am I work Project A. And 10am to 11am I work on Project B. What are other methods besides time blocking?
output_1:
Time blocking is a great method to allocate time to different tasks. However, it is not the only method that can be used. Time blocking can have a negative impact on your work life balance and is also not always an effective way to manage your time.

Another alternative method is to use a task management system, such as Todoist. This allows you to add multiple tasks to the system and then allocate time in chunks to each task. This allows you to see all of your tasks in one place and also ensures that you don’t spend too much time on one task at a time.

A final method is to use a time management system such as the pomodoro technique. This involves working on tasks in 25 minute intervals, with 5 minutes breaks in between. This technique is based on research that shows that people are most productive in 25 minute intervals, and that people can only concentrate for around 50 minutes at a time. By working in 25 minute intervals, you are able to maximise your concentration time and also reduce the amount of time spent on any one task.

 4. Do not work on other projects until all the items in the left side are done.
 5. When you have a deadline for a project, prioritize it.
 6. When you are done with a project, delete the project from your board and start a new project.

instruction: What is the best explanation of Newton’s laws?
output_1:
#### First Law of Motion
*  “An object will remain at rest or in uniform motion in a straight line unless acted upon by an external force.”

#### Second Law of Motion
*  “The change in momentum of an object is equal to the force that acted on the object multiplied by the displacement of the object.”

#### Third Law of Motion
*  “To every action there is always an equal and opposite reaction.”
output_2:
Newton’s laws of motion are 3 laws that describe the relationship between force, mass, and acceleration. These laws were discovered by Sir Isaac Newton and are as follows: 

• A body at rest remains at rest and a body in motion remains in motion at a constant speed unless acted upon by a net external force.  
• The acceleration of a body is directly proportional to the magnitude of the force acting on the body and inversely proportional to the mass of the body.  
• For every action there is an equal and opposite reaction.

The first law states that an object at rest will remain at rest and an object in motion will remain in motion and the second law states that the acceleration of an object is directly proportional to the net force acting on the object. Finally the third law states that for every action there is an equal and opposite reaction. These three laws are the foundation for our understanding of physics.

instruction: I'm buying a car for the first time, any advice?
output_1:
First of all, congratulations on your first car! The process of buying a car can seem a little overwhelming at first, but there are some simple tips and tricks that can help you navigate the process and come out with the car of your dreams.

The first step is to figure out what kind of car you want. Do you want a sedan, hatchback, SUV, or truck? Once you know what kind of car you want, you can start looking for specific models and features that meet your needs. There are plenty of great websites and apps that allow you to filter your search results to quickly find cars that match what you're looking for.

Another important thing to consider is your budget. How much can you realistically afford to spend on a car? It's important to be realistic about your budget because if you set your sights too high, you may end up settling on a car that you don't really want. On the other hand, if you set your budget too low, you may end up struggling to afford the car payments and insurance. It's a good idea to get pre-approved for a loan before you start shopping for a car. This will help you figure out how much you can afford, and it will also make the financing process go smoother when you find the car you want.

When you're ready to start looking for a car, it's a good idea to do some research online first. You can use sites like Cars.com or Edmunds.com to compare different makes and models, read reviews, and find out what other people are paying for the cars you're interested in. If you see a car that catches your eye, you can also use the websites to contact the dealer and ask them for more information.

When you're ready to start looking in person, it's a good idea to narrow down your search to a few cars. You can do this by looking at the features and specifications of the cars online and comparing them side by side. It's also a good idea to bring someone along with you when you test drive the cars. This person can be your voice of reason and help you make a decision.

Once you've found the car you want, you'll need to negotiate the price. The best way to negotiate is to do your research first. Look up the price of the car on sites like Kelley Blue Book or Edmunds.com and use that as your starting point. When you're ready to negotiate, you can try to lower the price by offering to pay cash or trade in your current car. You can also ask for additional features or services, such as free maintenance or a warranty extension. If the dealer isn't willing to lower the price, you can always walk away and look for a better deal elsewhere.

Buying a car doesn't have to be a stressful or intimidating experience. By following these tips, you can find the car of your dreams without any hassle.
output_2:
You have two big decisions to make, which car to buy, and which car dealership to buy it from.  Here are a few tips for each of those decisions:

For which car to buy, it's really important to do your research.  Visit car dealerships, test drive different models, and check out reviews online.  It's also important to know what kind of car you need.  Think about how many people will be riding in the car, and whether you need a large trunk or a lot of power.
